                <head>121. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On January 2, 1980, the trade reorganization plan, originally proposed by
                    Director of the Office of Management and Budget James McIntyre and Special Trade
                    Representative Robert Strauss, was promulgated with the issuance of Executive
                    Order 12188. Submitted to Congress by President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                        >Jimmy Carter</persName> in September 1979 and approved by Congress in
                    November, the plan renamed the Office of the Special Trade Representative to the
                    Office of the U.S. Trade Representative, and gave the office the authority to
                    develop U.S. trade policy. At that time, many of the trade programs were moved
                    from the Treasury Department to the Department of Commerce. For the text of
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName>’s remarks on signing the
                    executive order and <gloss target="#t_EO_1">E.O.</gloss> 12188, see <hi
                        rend="italic">Public Papers: <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName>,
                        1980–81,</hi> Book I, pages 5–11.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
